======================================================================
PART 1: FANO PLANE STRUCTURE
======================================================================
Fano lines (PG(2,F_2)):
  L0: [1, 2, 4]
  L1: [2, 3, 5]
  L2: [3, 4, 6]
  L3: [4, 5, 7]
  L4: [1, 5, 6]
  L5: [2, 6, 7]
  L6: [1, 3, 7]

Property: every pair of points lies on exactly λ=1 line
  ✓ Confirmed: 2-(7,3,1) BIBD (Steiner triple system S(2,3,7))

8 tournaments at n=3 as F_2^3:
  T_000 = [1→0, 2→0, 2→1]
  T_001 = [0→1, 2→0, 2→1]
  T_010 = [1→0, 0→2, 2→1]
  T_011 = [0→1, 0→2, 2→1]
  T_100 = [1→0, 2→0, 1→2]
  T_101 = [0→1, 2→0, 1→2]
  T_110 = [1→0, 0→2, 1→2]
  T_111 = [0→1, 0→2, 1→2]

Fano-tournament correspondence:
  F_2^3 has 8 elements = 8 tournaments on n=3
  PG(2,F_2) = (F_2^3\{0}) / ~ has 7 points
  Each Fano line = 3 collinear points = 3 tournaments sharing a property
  |GL(3,F_2)| = 168 = 168 = 8 × 21
  168/24 = 7 = 7 = H_forb_1

======================================================================
PART 2: THE 2-(10,4,2) BIBD AT n=6
======================================================================
10 partition pairs ({A,B} with |A|=|B|=3, A∪B={0,...,5}):
  P 0: {0,1,2} | {3,4,5}
  P 1: {0,1,3} | {2,4,5}
  P 2: {0,1,4} | {2,3,5}
  P 3: {0,1,5} | {2,3,4}
  P 4: {0,2,3} | {1,4,5}
  P 5: {0,2,4} | {1,3,5}
  P 6: {0,2,5} | {1,3,4}
  P 7: {0,3,4} | {1,2,5}
  P 8: {0,3,5} | {1,2,4}
  P 9: {0,4,5} | {1,2,3}

2-(10,4,2) BIBD parameters:
  v=10 points, b=15 blocks, k=4 points/block, r=6 blocks/point, λ=2
  Fisher: b=15 ≥ v=10 ✓
  λ(v-1)=r(k-1): 2·9=6·3=18 ✓
  bk=vr: 15·4=10·6=60 ✓

======================================================================
PART 3: THE DESIGN LADDER
======================================================================

Designs emerging from tournament topology:
  n=3: PG(2,F_2) = 2-(7,3,1) Steiner triple system S(2,3,7)
       7 pts, 7 lines, 3 pts/line, 3 lines/pt, λ=1
  n=6: 2-(10,4,2) BIBD
       10 pts, 15 blocks, 4 pts/block, 6 blocks/pt, λ=2

Numerological connections:
  n=3: v=7=2^3-1 (Mersenne), b=7, k=3, λ=1
  n=6: v=10=C(5,2), b=15=C(6,2), k=4, λ=2
  Ratio b/v: n=3 → 7/7=1, n=6 → 15/10=3/2
  Step: n=3→n=6 is n→2n

======================================================================
PART 4: PETERSEN GRAPH CONNECTION
======================================================================
Petersen graph: 10 vertices, 15 edges
Vertices (2-subsets of {{0,1,2,3,4}}):
  V0: {0, 1}
  V1: {0, 2}
  V2: {0, 3}
  V3: {0, 4}
  V4: {1, 2}
  V5: {1, 3}
  V6: {1, 4}
  V7: {2, 3}
  V8: {2, 4}
  V9: {3, 4}

15 edges (disjoint pairs):
  E0: V0={0, 1} — V7={2, 3}
  E1: V0={0, 1} — V8={2, 4}
  E2: V0={0, 1} — V9={3, 4}
  E3: V1={0, 2} — V5={1, 3}
  E4: V1={0, 2} — V6={1, 4}
  E5: V1={0, 2} — V9={3, 4}
  E6: V2={0, 3} — V4={1, 2}
  E7: V2={0, 3} — V6={1, 4}
  E8: V2={0, 3} — V8={2, 4}
  E9: V3={0, 4} — V4={1, 2}
  E10: V3={0, 4} — V5={1, 3}
  E11: V3={0, 4} — V7={2, 3}
  E12: V4={1, 2} — V9={3, 4}
  E13: V5={1, 3} — V8={2, 4}
  E14: V6={1, 4} — V7={2, 3}

Bijection: partition pairs of {0,...,5} → 2-subsets of {0,...,4}:
  P0: (0, 1, 2)|(3, 4, 5) → {3, 4}
  P1: (0, 1, 3)|(2, 4, 5) → {2, 4}
  P2: (0, 1, 4)|(2, 3, 5) → {2, 3}
  P3: (0, 1, 5)|(2, 3, 4) → {0, 1}
  P4: (0, 2, 3)|(1, 4, 5) → {1, 4}
  P5: (0, 2, 4)|(1, 3, 5) → {1, 3}
  P6: (0, 2, 5)|(1, 3, 4) → {0, 2}
  P7: (0, 3, 4)|(1, 2, 5) → {1, 2}
  P8: (0, 3, 5)|(1, 2, 4) → {0, 3}
  P9: (0, 4, 5)|(1, 2, 3) → {0, 4}

Bijection to Petersen vertices: False

======================================================================
PART 5: THE FANO → BIBD CHAIN
======================================================================
Symmetry groups:
  Fano: |Aut(PG(2,F_2))| = |GL(3,F_2)| = 168 = 8 × 21
  Petersen: |Aut(Petersen)| = |S_5| = 120 = 5!
  S_6 acts on 10 partitions: |S_6| = 720 = 6!
  720/120 = 6 (index of Aut(Petersen) in S_6)

  S_6 is the ONLY symmetric group with an outer automorphism!
  The outer automorphism of S_6 maps:
    points {0,...,5} → partition pairs (our 10 BIBD points)
    transpositions → synthemes (triple transpositions)
  This is WHY the 10 partition pairs have such rich structure!

======================================================================
PART 6: THE 7-15-21 CHAIN
======================================================================
Three key numbers in our design ladder:
   7 = 2^3 - 1 = C(3,1) + C(3,2) + C(3,3) = Fano points = H_forb_1
  15 = 2^4 - 1 = C(6,2) = BIBD blocks = Petersen edges = PG(3,F_2) points
  21 = 3 × 7  = C(7,2) = H_forb_2

As Mersenne-like numbers:
   7 = 2^3 - 1 (Mersenne prime M_3)
  15 = 2^4 - 1 (NOT prime, = 3 × 5)
  21 = NOT Mersenne (21 = 3 × 7, but 2^? - 1 never = 21)
  31 = 2^5 - 1 (Mersenne prime M_5)
  63 = 2^6 - 1 (NOT prime, = 7 × 9)

As triangular numbers:
   T_n = n(n+1)/2
   7 = NOT triangular
  15 = T_5 = 5×6/2
  21 = T_6 = 6×7/2 = C(7,2)

As C(n,2):
  C(4,2) =  6:  arcs in n=4 tournament
  C(5,2) = 10:  arcs in n=5, BIBD points, Petersen vertices
  C(6,2) = 15:  arcs in n=6, BIBD blocks, Petersen edges
  C(7,2) = 21 = H_forb_2

THE DEEP PATTERN:
  The BIBD lives in the space C(5,2) × C(6,2) = 10 × 15
  The Fano plane lives in the space 7 × 7
  Tournament arcs at n=6: C(6,2) = 15 = BIBD blocks
  Tournament arcs at n=7: C(7,2) = 21 = H_forb_2
  The FORBIDDEN value H=21 = the dimension of the n=7 tournament cube!

======================================================================
PART 7: PREDICTING n=7 DESIGN
======================================================================
n=7: Number of disjoint 3-subset pairs = 70
  (Each pair leaves 1 vertex uncovered)
  Compare: n=6 had 10 complementary pairs

  n=6 design: v=10 points, b=15 blocks, on C(6,3)/2 = 10 partitions
  n=7 design: v=70 'points' (disjoint 3-subset pairs)
              What are the blocks? Need to enumerate n=7 tournaments...
              C(7,2)=21 arcs → 2^21 = 2097152 tournaments (feasible but slow)

  max disjoint 3-cycles at n=7: floor(7/3) = 2
  So α₂ at n=7 is still about PAIRS of disjoint 3-cycles
  Each 3-subset either forms a 3-cycle (prob 1/4) or not
  A disjoint pair (A,B) is 'both-cyclic' with prob 1/16 (independent)
  Expected α₂ ≈ 70 × 1/16 ≈ 4.4

======================================================================
PART 8: S_6 OUTER AUTOMORPHISM AND TOURNAMENTS
======================================================================
Synthemes (perfect matchings of {0,...,5}): 15
  S 0: ((0, 1), (2, 3), (4, 5))
  S 1: ((0, 1), (2, 4), (3, 5))
  S 2: ((0, 1), (2, 5), (3, 4))
  S 3: ((0, 2), (1, 3), (4, 5))
  S 4: ((0, 2), (1, 4), (3, 5))
  S 5: ((0, 2), (1, 5), (3, 4))
  S 6: ((0, 3), (1, 2), (4, 5))
  S 7: ((0, 3), (1, 4), (2, 5))
  S 8: ((0, 3), (1, 5), (2, 4))
  S 9: ((0, 4), (1, 2), (3, 5))
  S10: ((0, 4), (1, 3), (2, 5))
  S11: ((0, 4), (1, 5), (2, 3))
  S12: ((0, 5), (1, 2), (3, 4))
  S13: ((0, 5), (1, 3), (2, 4))
  S14: ((0, 5), (1, 4), (2, 3))

  15 transpositions ↔ 15 synthemes via outer automorphism of S_6
  15 = C(6,2) = number of arcs in n=6 tournament
  15 = number of BIBD blocks in our 2-(10,4,2)
  ALL THREE COUNTS ARE 15!

  Sylvester's duad-syntheme-total structure:
  15 duads (2-subsets of {0,...,5})
  15 synthemes (perfect matchings)
  6 totals (each = 5 synthemes partitioning the 15 duads)
  This is the OUTER AUTOMORPHISM of S_6 made visible!

